SIMPLE: fossilize
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fossilize
<hw>Fos"sil*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Fossilized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Fossilizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>fossiliser</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To convert into a fossil;
to petrify; <as>as, to <ex>fossilize</ex> bones or wood</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to become antiquated, rigid, or fixed, as
by fossilization; to mummify; to deaden.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ten layers of birthdays on a woman's head⟦br⟧
Are apt to <qex>fossilize</qex> her girlish mirth.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs.
Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fossilize</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fossilize
<hw>Fos"sil*ize</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become
fossil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To become antiquated, rigid, or fixed, beyond the
influence of change or progress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fossilized</ent>⟦br⟧
